{
  "card_id": "directional_candle",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Directional Candle",
  "aliases": [
    "directional move",
    "one-sided move"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A candle where price moves predominantly in one direction, with a small wick relative to the body. Bearish: opens, makes a high, trends lower to a low, closes near low. Bullish: opens, makes a low, trends higher to a high, closes near high. It breaks only one side of the prior candle's high or low, not both.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Bearish: open above close, upper wick (high minus open) small, sustained downtrend after high; close near low of period.",
    "Bullish: open below close, lower wick (open minus low) small, sustained uptrend after low; close near high of period.",
    "Wick size (open to extreme) is noticeably smaller than the body range (open to close).",
    "On lower time frames, the high or low forms early, then displacement continues in one direction for most of the period.",
    "The candle breaks only the prior candle's high (Buy Side Liquidity) or only its low (Sell Side Liquidity), not both.",
    "Exclude candles that break both prior high and low (Outside Bar).",
    "Exclude candles that break neither side (Indecision Candle).",
    "After three consecutive directional candles, anticipate a different candle type (reversal or indecision)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Directional candles signal strong momentum and continuation bias. They confirm the intended direction and support expecting further expansion in the same direction for the next candle or session. Used to validate daily bias and anticipate lower-time-frame delivery of open-high-low-close (or open-low-high-close) sequences. For Draw On Liquidity: upward break targets higher liquidity (e.g., Previous Day High); downward break targets lower liquidity (e.g., Previous Day Low).",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing a candle with a large wick and small body as directional, when it is actually a reversal or indecision candle.",
    "Not confirming sustained directional movement on lower time frames, leading to misinterpretation of a choppy period.",
    "Expecting a fourth consecutive directional candle after three expansions without considering a probable reversal or consolidation.",
    "Mistaking an Outside Bar (breaks both prior high and low) for a directional candle.",
    "Mistaking an Indecision Candle (breaks neither side) for a directional candle.",
    "On lower time frames, seeing the initial small counter-move (forming the wick) and mistaking it for a reversal before price confirms the main direction."
  ],
